{
  "title": "The Apocalyptic World View",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cc6d4b0664640451",
      "text": "To cultivate an apocalyptic view of the world is not to be confused with that analytical pessimism which, for example, [[Antonio Gramsci]] granted to the critical spirit - as an adversary to the optimism of action. The apocalyptic world view is rather related to the idea of [[catastrophe]], whose deliberate projection, according to [[Theodor W. Adorno]], expresses that one also wants the feared somewhere. In fact, it is not a theoretical but a mythical construction. And like all myths, the apocalyptic worldview arises out of an insoluble contradiction. It arises where the unwillingness against a fundamental change of the conditions is greater than the insight that it would be the only saving thing. Thus, marching into ruin with one's eyes open, one must at least lend this ruin transcendental grandeur or media glamor. And since a change from within is inconceivable, it can only be longed for as a catastrophe from without."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0f30938f63dcf8aa",
      "text": "> The apocalyptic worldview corresponds to an escape from history into myth.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bd6c4acff65c2cff",
      "text": "It is not for nothing that Olaf Scholz has linked the proclamation of a »Zeitenwende«/\"turning point in time\" with military rearmament, and since almost everyone agrees with him, from Bild to the so-called quality media, from eco-liberals to half-Nazis, the longed-for turning point must lie in this: The complicated democracy and its even more complicated civil society, which already did not quite prove themselves in the pandemic, are to be transformed into a defensible nation. The military, just now a laughingstock with more Nazi conspiracies than functioning material, is moving politically and rhetorically back to center stage. The impending doom and the longed-for turn of the times provide this turn of events with previously impossible broad support.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b521196278bca5c9",
      "text": "The transcendence of the downfall serves on the one hand the personal excuse - I can't do anything for it and couldn't do anything against it - and on the other hand the narcissistic relief - if I am to go down, then all the others too (best still before me). Only if many things are broken, I could become new. In other words: The gigantic problem, which cannot find a solution, gives birth as a monster to a negative image of redemption. For still further insoluble contradictions open up even to committed people: If (for example) the ecological catastrophe is to be averted, this could cause a social catastrophe. If the climate is to be saved, then overexploitation of nature must be committed for this. If one wants to conquer a virus, one must give up freedom. And regardless of who wins the war, it has taken us further away from peace than ever before. The apocalyptic world view corresponds to an escape from history into myth.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5d345205d869f940",
      "text": "In the idea of the apocalypse, the experience of historical powerlessness is processed. When the whole world perishes, this also erases one's own guilt in it, and a war like the one in Ukraine has such an apocalyptic effect that it erases, as it were, the question of its \"madeness\". Who can be to blame for it, if not a devil, possibly? But the myth also covers up how powerless one is at the mercy of one's own inner world. Where to put pacifism when it is demanded that solidarity be inseparably linked to the militarization of thought and action? Is suddenly commanded what just seemed degoutant, the flag waving, the arms supplying, the nationalism, the propaganda? When one sees the pictures and hears the speeches, one thinks involuntarily of Karl Kraus' \"The Last Days of Mankind\" from the First World War. The discourses dissolve into an obscene, kitschy and, at the core, inhuman background noise.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "da0f598e30a727fc",
      "text": "Finally, the apocalyptic worldview also arises from the pitfalls of prohibitions on thought and speech. Certain things may no longer be brought up, not only because doing so risks one's status in mainstream culture, but also because they simply no longer make for a coherent narrative. It is a paradox of the apocalyptic worldview: even more than the fear of the end of the world, it is generated by the fear of being isolated, outcast, ostracized. While those who pursue historical analysis are in danger of becoming isolated, the apocalyptic worldview creates a community. That alone makes it so popular. Imagine it's the turn of the times, and you don't join in!\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "dc27887d7a6690fb",
      "text": "But is this not the chronicle of a war that has been announced? We have to look into the economic departments of our picture and sound machines to get a scandalous suspicion. There we learn, from the usual suspects from the think tanks of neoliberalism, two things. First, Russia is one of the globalization losers. While the West expanded politically, militarily, and economically to the East, Russia remained a powerful but economically second-rate state from which to obtain raw materials while exporting luxury goods for the so-called oligarchs. (Porsche had taken its profits in Russia to record highs despite the pandemic). Second, Russia cannot become a major economic power without Ukraine. The Russian government's plan to create a major economic antagonist to the EU's single market, the Eurasian Economic Union, was thwarted in 2014 by Ukraine's association with the EU. Suddenly, war, just a terrible dream of a despot gone wild, who wants to lead his empire to \"old greatness,\" who in his barbarism clings to times and images long past, and in the process, instead of a new world order, creates the great chaos, acquires a logic within the world narrative of neoliberalism. In our history! So what if the invasion of post-imperialist Russia on Ukraine, which has just started on the road to democracy, would not be a break with this world narrative but, conversely, a consequence of it? Then the crimes of this war would no longer be something that has nothing to do with us, but would be ours as well. This bleak realization is also obscured in the apocalyptic image.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "77d0036e68240a3b",
      "text": "The real catastrophe, then, would be for us television viewers, idly and at the same time ominously connected to the medium's destructiveness, to witness a disaster, well, a disaster, in which we are not so innocent as the external drama indicates. One can guess: That Putin and his entourage are acting so clearly criminally does not explain everything about this war. And the war does not at all explain everything about the longed-for change of times.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "adef952f05396bcc",
      "text": "And now another absurd double bind situation emerges - or, strictly speaking, another concretion of the dialectic of impending ecological and social catastrophe. War displaces technical solutions to reduce CO2 emissions, puts dirty technologies back in business, stifles social resistance, but conversely, the expectation of ecological catastrophe is also a means of preventing any lessons from this war. Where should we look? To the dramatic weather events almost everywhere in the world that point to an imminent end of the outside world as we knew it, to the fact that governments almost everywhere are neither willing nor able to enforce protective measures against the virus in a socially acceptable way, so that a new wave of collapsing people and collapsing health systems is imminent, pointing to a near end of \"society\" as we knew it - or to the war crimes and their victims, pointing to a near end of human history as we knew it? We are like our administrative bodies, our experts, our explanatory systems, and our supply chains: overwhelmed. The apocalyptic worldview is the transcendence of overwhelm. And it is the breeding ground for a turn of the times in which not only more or less democratic governance but also the political economy is being remodeled. The narrative of great unification through the globalization of markets is over, and a new narrative of political-military capitalism is beginning.\n\n"
    },
