        "id": "cc6d4b0664640451",
        "text": "To cultivate an apocalyptic view of the world is not to be confused with that analytical pessimism which, for example, [[Antonio Gramsci]] granted to the critical spirit - as an adversary to the optimism of action. The apocalyptic world view is rather related to the idea of [[catastrophe]], whose deliberate projection, according to [[Theodor W. Adorno]], expresses that one also wants the feared somewhere. In fact, it is not a theoretical but a mythical construction. And like all myths, the apocalyptic worldview arises out of an insoluble contradiction. It arises where the unwillingness against a fundamental change of the conditions is greater than the insight that it would be the only saving thing. Thus, marching into ruin with one's eyes open, one must at least lend this ruin transcendental grandeur or media glamor. And since a change from within is inconceivable, it can only be longed for as a catastrophe from without."
